= Centre Economic Planning

The Centre Region holds both a mixture of industrial and agricultural production, as well as acts as bridge between the industrialised North and the agricultural South, not to mention the capital. Though certainly not as important as the other regions in terms of specialisation or production, the Centre is pivotal for trade and movement of both goods and people between the two regions.

@central_menu

[? if left_eco_adopted : With the Central Economic Plan, the State Planning Committee has drafted up plans to improve the economic situation regarding the Central Region. Our economic direction means, thankfully, we will be able to directly order workers to their necessary positions. ?]

[? if right_eco_adopted : The New Economic Plan has allowed us to take a more hands-off approach to managing the economic situation. Though not directly managing the situation, we can certainly nudge independent and private enterprise to aid us in economic recovery. ?]

[? if both_eco_adopted : Our Regional Dualism Policy will, unfortunately, impact the Centre the most, considering its importance as a bridge between the two regions and policies. Though we will naturally need to recover the region, its importance, as least temporarily, will be infrastructural purposes and to act as a trading region. ?]

Every action will be impacted by the loyalties and efficiency of our bureaucracy.

- @industry_delegate: Reallocate Central Industrial Production.
- @industry_expand_cec: Expand the Industrial Factories.
- @industry_expand_nep: Subsidise Industrial Production
- @supply_railways_expand: Expand the Freight Railways.
- @central_supply_repair: Repair Existing Infrastructure.
- @central_supply_trade: Construct and Delegate Open Market Regions.
- @agriculture_delegate: Reallocate Agricultural Production.
- @agriculture_expand_cec: Expand the Agricultural Fields.
- @agriculture_expand_nep: Subsidise Farmers and Purchase Yields.
- @agriculture_aid: Could we utilise the Radio for Agricultural Purposes?
- @root: Don't touch economic policy for now.
- @easy_discard

